---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout title="Mahavakyas - The Great Statements">
  <main class="max-w-5xl mx-auto px-4 py-12">
    <header class="mb-12 text-center">
      <h1 class="text-4xl font-semibold text-accent-saffron mb-3">
        Mahavakyas
      </h1>
      <p class="text-text-secondary text-lg">
        The Four Great Statements of the Upanishads
      </p>
    </header>

    <!-- Introduction -->
    <div class="mb-12 bg-bg-white border-l-4 border-accent-saffron p-6 rounded">
      <p class="text-text-primary leading-relaxed mb-4">
        The <strong>Mahavakyas</strong> (महावाक्यानि) are the four great statements from the Upanishads 
        that directly reveal the fundamental truth of Advaita Vedanta - the identity of Atman (individual self) 
        and Brahman (ultimate reality).
      </p>
      <p class="text-text-secondary leading-relaxed">
        Each Mahavakya comes from one of the four Vedas and points to the same truth from different angles. 
        They are considered the most direct expressions of supreme knowledge in all of Vedic literature.
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- The Four Mahavakyas -->
    <div class="space-y-10">
      <!-- 1. Prajnanam Brahma -->
      <section class="bg-gradient-to-br from-bg-white to-bg-sanskrit border-2 border-border rounded-xl p-8 shadow-lg">
        <div class="flex items-start gap-4 mb-6">
          <div class="text-4xl font-bold text-accent-saffron bg-bg-sanskrit px-4 py-2 rounded">1</div>
          <div>
            <h2 class="text-3xl font-semibold text-accent-saffron mb-2">प्रज्ञानं ब्रह्म</h2>
            <p class="text-2xl text-text-primary italic">Prajnanam Brahma</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        
        <div class="space-y-4">
          <div class="bg-bg-white p-4 rounded">
            <p class="text-lg font-semibold text-text-primary mb-2">Translation:</p>
            <p class="text-text-secondary">"Consciousness is Brahman" or "Knowledge is Brahman"</p>
          </div>
          
          <div class="bg-bg-white p-4 rounded">
            <p class="text-lg font-semibold text-text-primary mb-2">Source:</p>
            <p class="text-text-secondary">Aitareya Upanishad 3.3 (Rig Veda)</p>
          </div>
          
          <div class="bg-bg-white p-4 rounded">
            <p class="text-lg font-semibold text-text-primary mb-2">Meaning:</p>
            <p class="text-text-secondary leading-relaxed">
              This Mahavakya establishes the nature of Brahman as pure consciousness (prajnana). 
              It reveals that ultimate reality is not inert matter or a distant deity, but the very 
              consciousness that illuminates all experiences. The awareness by which you know everything 
              else - that awareness itself is Brahman.
            </p>
          </div>
          
          <div class="bg-bg-sanskrit p-4 rounded">
            <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary italic">
              Key Teaching: Brahman is of the nature of pure consciousness, self-luminous and all-pervading.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- 2. Tat Tvam Asi -->
      <section class="bg-gradient-to-br from-bg-white to-bg-sanskrit border-2 border-border rounded-xl p-8 shadow-lg">
        <div class="flex items-start gap-4 mb-6">
          <div class="text-4xl font-bold text-accent-saffron bg-bg-sanskrit px-4 py-2 rounded">2</div>
          <div>
            <h2 class="text-3xl font-semibold text-accent-saffron mb-2">तत् त्वम् असि</h2>
            <p class="text-2xl text-text-primary italic">Tat Tvam Asi</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        
        <div class="space-y-4">
          <div class="bg-bg-white p-4 rounded">
            <p class="text-lg font-semibold text-text-primary mb-2">Translation:</p>
            <p class="text-text-secondary">"That Thou Art" or "You are That"</p>
          </div>
          
          <div class="bg-bg-white p-4 rounded">
            <p class="text-lg font-semibold text-text-primary mb-2">Source:</p>
            <p class="text-text-secondary">Chandogya Upanishad 6.8.7 (Sama Veda)</p>
          </div>
          
          <div class="bg-bg-white p-4 rounded">
            <p class="text-lg font-semibold text-text-primary mb-2">Meaning:</p>
            <p class="text-text-secondary leading-relaxed">
              This is perhaps the most famous Mahavakya. "Tat" (That) refers to Brahman, the absolute reality. 
              "Tvam" (Thou) refers to the individual self. "Asi" (Art) establishes their identity. 
              The guru Uddalaka repeats this teaching nine times to his son Svetaketu, emphasizing 
              that you are not a limited individual, but the infinite Brahman itself.
            </p>
          </div>
          
          <div class="bg-bg-sanskrit p-4 rounded">
            <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary italic">
              Key Teaching: The individual self (Atman) and the cosmic reality (Brahman) are one and the same.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- 3. Ayam Atma Brahma -->
      <section class="bg-gradient-to-br from-bg-white to-bg-sanskrit border-2 border-border rounded-xl p-8 shadow-lg">
        <div class="flex items-start gap-4 mb-6">
          <div class="text-4xl font-bold text-accent-saffron bg-bg-sanskrit px-4 py-2 rounded">3</div>
          <div>
            <h2 class="text-3xl font-semibold text-accent-saffron mb-2">अयम् आत्मा ब्रह्म</h2>
            <p class="text-2xl text-text-primary italic">Ayam Atma Brahma</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        
        <div class="space-y-4">
          <div class="bg-bg-white p-4 rounded">
            <p class="text-lg font-semibold text-text-primary mb-2">Translation:</p>
            <p class="text-text-secondary">"This Self is Brahman"</p>
          </div>
          
          <div class="bg-bg-white p-4 rounded">
            <p class="text-lg font-semibold text-text-primary mb-2">Source:</p>
            <p class="text-text-secondary">Mandukya Upanishad 2 (Atharva Veda)</p>
          </div>
          
          <div class="bg-bg-white p-4 rounded">
            <p class="text-lg font-semibold text-text-primary mb-2">Meaning:</p>
            <p class="text-text-secondary leading-relaxed">
              This Mahavakya uses the demonstrative "Ayam" (This) to point directly at the Self. 
              It's like pointing at yourself and declaring "This very Self that I am is Brahman." 
              The directness of this statement removes all speculation - Brahman is not something distant 
              to be attained, but your own innermost Self to be recognized here and now.
            </p>
          </div>
          
          <div class="bg-bg-sanskrit p-4 rounded">
            <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary italic">
              Key Teaching: Your essential nature, the Self (Atman), is none other than Brahman - the ultimate reality.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- 4. Aham Brahmasmi -->
      <section class="bg-gradient-to-br from-bg-white to-bg-sanskrit border-2 border-border rounded-xl p-8 shadow-lg">
        <div class="flex items-start gap-4 mb-6">
          <div class="text-4xl font-bold text-accent-saffron bg-bg-sanskrit px-4 py-2 rounded">4</div>
          <div>
            <h2 class="text-3xl font-semibold text-accent-saffron mb-2">अहम् ब्रह्मास्मि</h2>
            <p class="text-2xl text-text-primary italic">Aham Brahmasmi</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        
        <div class="space-y-4">
          <div class="bg-bg-white p-4 rounded">
            <p class="text-lg font-semibold text-text-primary mb-2">Translation:</p>
            <p class="text-text-secondary">"I am Brahman"</p>
          </div>
          
          <div class="bg-bg-white p-4 rounded">
            <p class="text-lg font-semibold text-text-primary mb-2">Source:</p>
            <p class="text-text-secondary">Brihadaranyaka Upanishad 1.4.10 (Yajur Veda)</p>
          </div>
          
          <div class="bg-bg-white p-4 rounded">
            <p class="text-lg font-semibold text-text-primary mb-2">Meaning:</p>
            <p class="text-text-secondary leading-relaxed">
              This Mahavakya represents the culmination of knowledge - the direct realization and declaration 
              of one's true nature. "Aham" (I) is not the ego or limited individual, but the pure "I" - 
              consciousness itself. This statement transforms understanding into being, knowledge into realization. 
              It is the voice of the liberated sage who has transcended all limitation.
            </p>
          </div>
          
          <div class="bg-bg-sanskrit p-4 rounded">
            <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary italic">
              Key Teaching: The direct assertion of identity with Brahman - the culmination of self-knowledge.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>
    </div>

    <!-- Understanding Mahavakyas -->
    <div class="mt-12 bg-bg-white border-2 border-accent-saffron rounded-lg p-8">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-accent-saffron mb-6">Understanding the Mahavakyas</h2>
      
      <div class="space-y-6 text-text-secondary">
        <div>
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-text-primary mb-2">Three Types of Meaning</h3>
          <p class="mb-2">Traditional Vedantic interpretation uses three levels:</p>
          <ul class="ml-6 space-y-2">
            <li>
              <strong class="text-text-primary">Vachyartha</strong> (Primary meaning) - 
              The literal, direct meaning of the words
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong class="text-text-primary">Lakshanaartha</strong> (Implied meaning) - 
              The indicated meaning when the primary meaning doesn't fit
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong class="text-text-primary">Lakshya-lakshana</strong> (Mutual implication) - 
              The synthesis that reconciles apparent contradictions
            </li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div>
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-text-primary mb-2">Progressive Revelation</h3>
          <p>Each Mahavakya approaches the same truth from a different angle:</p>
          <ul class="ml-6 space-y-2 mt-2">
            <li>• <strong>Prajnanam Brahma</strong> - Reveals the nature of Brahman</li>
            <li>• <strong>Tat Tvam Asi</strong> - Establishes the identity (upadesha vakya)</li>
            <li>• <strong>Ayam Atma Brahma</strong> - Points directly at the Self</li>
            <li>• <strong>Aham Brahmasmi</strong> - The declaration of realization</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div>
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-text-primary mb-2">The Methodology</h3>
          <p class="mb-2">
            The Mahavakyas are not mere philosophical statements to be believed. They are:
          </p>
          <ul class="ml-6 space-y-2">
            <li>• <strong>Pramana</strong> (means of knowledge) - Valid sources of direct knowledge about the Self</li>
            <li>• Revealed through <strong>Sravana</strong> (listening), clarified through <strong>Manana</strong> (reflection), 
                and realized through <strong>Nididhyasana</strong> (meditation)</li>
            <li>• The guru unfolds their meaning systematically, removing the student's misconceptions layer by layer</li>
            <li>• Understanding leads to <strong>Aparoksha Jnana</strong> - direct, immediate knowledge of one's true nature</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Important Warning -->
    <div class="mt-12 p-6 bg-gradient-to-r from-bg-sanskrit to-bg-white border-2 border-accent-saffron rounded-lg">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-accent-saffron mb-3">⚠️ Essential Guidance</h3>
      <p class="text-text-secondary leading-relaxed mb-3">
        The Mahavakyas are extremely subtle and profound teachings. Their proper understanding requires:
      </p>
      <ul class="ml-6 space-y-2 text-text-secondary">
        <li>• A qualified guru who has realized their truth</li>
        <li>• Systematic preparation through study of introductory texts</li>
        <li>• Development of the four qualifications (Sadhana Chatushtaya)</li>
        <li>• Patient, humble inquiry under guidance</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="text-text-secondary leading-relaxed mt-3">
        Attempting to understand or practice these statements without proper preparation and guidance 
        can lead to intellectual confusion or spiritual arrogance. These are not affirmations to be 
        mechanically repeated, but truths to be unfolded by a competent teacher.
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- Navigation -->
    <div class="mt-8 flex justify-center gap-4">
      <a href="/concepts/key-concepts" class="px-6 py-3 bg-bg-white border-2 border-accent-saffron text-accent-saffron rounded-lg hover:bg-bg-sanskrit transition-colors">
        ← Key Concepts
      </a>
      <a href="/concepts/glossary" class="px-6 py-3 bg-bg-white border-2 border-accent-saffron text-accent-saffron rounded-lg hover:bg-bg-sanskrit transition-colors">
        View Glossary
      </a>
    </div>
  </main>
</BaseLayout>
